    "narrative": "For Ghost Ride the WHIP on this April 25th, the cornerstone of our lineup is undoubtedly **Corbin Carroll**, who carries an elite 87.14 projection into his matchup against Germ\u00e1n M\u00e1rquez. The combination of M\u00e1rquez\u2019s elevated 5.26 xERA and a generous 86% stolen base success rate against his delivery makes **Corbin Carroll** our highest-ceiling asset today; we are heavily prioritizing his speed potential to address our scarcity targets. Meanwhile, **Seiya Suzuki** offers excellent value at 68.49, buoyed by a significant +19% boost from Roki Sasaki\u2019s high xERA and favorable wind conditions that favor his power profile. **Brice Turang** also earns a strong recommendation at 65.25, benefiting from the top-of-the-order bump and a solid matchup against Mitch Keller to keep the basepaths churning.\n\nStrategic lineup construction forced some difficult calls, particularly regarding **Max Muncy**. He logged a respectable 49.36, but was ultimately edged out by the superior power-hitting matchups of **Giancarlo Stanton** and **Josh Naylor**. While **Max Muncy** carries upside, the combination of **Josh Naylor**\u2019s +10% SP skill advantage and the specific lineup placement of our primary starters proved more optimal under the current constraints. We are also keeping a close watch on **Luis Campusano** and **Alex Freeland**, both of whom are currently relegated to the bottom of the order; their scores remain marginal, and should the official lineups confirm them in the 8th or 9th spots, their efficiency will suffer accordingly.\n\nRisk management remains a primary focus as we navigate several \"Lineup Pending\" designations. We have avoided the disaster of a zero-point return from **Mickey Moniak**, whose game is already flagged for a rainout. Furthermore, we are proceeding with caution regarding **Vinnie Pasquantino**; while he is a staple, his 55.60 score is weighed down by a difficult 2.35 xERA matchup against Walbert Urena. Similarly, **Austin Riley** remains on the bench not just due to the optimizer\u2019s preference for current efficiency, but because he faces an elite arm in Zack Wheeler, which suppresses his overall projected output. Ensure all caps are monitored closely, as the gap between our top-tier plays and our marginal starts is widening.",
